## GraphQL Integration

### Craft CMS Client

```typescript
// lib/craft.ts
const CRAFT_GRAPHQL_URL = process.env.CRAFT_GRAPHQL_URL!;
const CRAFT_GRAPHQL_TOKEN = process.env.CRAFT_GRAPHQL_TOKEN!;

export async function craftQuery<T>(
  query: string,
  variables?: Record<string, any>
): Promise<T> {
  const res = await fetch(CRAFT_GRAPHQL_URL, {
    method: 'POST',
    headers: {
      'Content-Type': 'application/json',
      'Authorization': `Bearer ${CRAFT_GRAPHQL_TOKEN}`,
    },
    body: JSON.stringify({ query, variables }),
    next: { revalidate: 3600 }, // ISR: revalidate hourly
  });

  const json = await res.json();
  if (json.errors) throw new Error(json.errors[0].message);
  return json.data;
}
```

### Example Queries

```graphql
# Fetch entries
query GetBlogPosts($limit: Int) {
  entries(section: "blog", limit: $limit, orderBy: "postDate DESC") {
    id
    title
    slug
    postDate
    ... on blog_blog_Entry {
      summary
      featuredImage {
        url @transform(width: 800, height: 450, mode: "crop")
        alt
      }
    }
  }
}

# Single entry
query GetPage($slug: [String]) {
  entry(section: "pages", slug: $slug) {
    title
    ... on pages_pages_Entry {
      body
      seoDescription
    }
  }
}
```

### Using in Server Components

```tsx
// app/blog/page.tsx
import { craftQuery } from '@/lib/craft';
import { BLOG_POSTS_QUERY } from '@/lib/queries';

export default async function BlogPage() {
  const { entries } = await craftQuery(BLOG_POSTS_QUERY, { limit: 10 });

  return (
    <main>
      <h1>Blog</h1>
      {entries.map((post) => (
        <article key={post.slug}>
          <Link href={`/blog/${post.slug}`}>
            <h2>{post.title}</h2>
          </Link>
          <p>{post.summary}</p>
        </article>
      ))}
    </main>
  );
}
```

## Component Patterns

### Server Components (default)
```tsx
// app/page.tsx — Server Component by default
export default async function HomePage() {
  const data = await craftQuery(HOME_QUERY);
  return <main><h1>{data.entry.title}</h1></main>;
}
```

### Client Components
```tsx
'use client';
import { useState } from 'react';

export function SearchForm() {
  const [query, setQuery] = useState('');
  return (
    <input value={query} onChange={(e) => setQuery(e.target.value)} />
  );
}
```

### Dynamic Routes with Craft CMS
```tsx
// app/blog/[slug]/page.tsx
import { notFound } from 'next/navigation';

export default async function PostPage({ params }: { params: { slug: string } }) {
  const { entry } = await craftQuery(SINGLE_POST_QUERY, { slug: [params.slug] });
  if (!entry) notFound();

  return <article><h1>{entry.title}</h1></article>;
}

export async function generateStaticParams() {
  const { entries } = await craftQuery(ALL_SLUGS_QUERY);
  return entries.map((e) => ({ slug: e.slug }));
}

export async function generateMetadata({ params }) {
  const { entry } = await craftQuery(SINGLE_POST_QUERY, { slug: [params.slug] });
  return { title: entry?.title, description: entry?.seoDescription };
}
```

## Coding Standards

### PHP (Craft CMS)
- Follow PSR-12 coding standards
- Use type hints for parameters and return types

### TypeScript (Next.js)
- Use strict mode; no `any` type
- Define interfaces for all props and API responses
- Prefer Server Components; use `'use client'` only for interactivity

### CSS
- Use Tailwind utility classes
- Mobile-first responsive design
- Use `next/image` for all images

## Important Notes

1. **Always use `ddev` prefix** for backend CLI commands
2. **Project config**: Changes sync via `config/project/` YAML files
3. **Environment variables**: Backend in `.env`, frontend uses `NEXT_PUBLIC_` prefix for client-side
4. **GraphQL tokens**: Keep server-side only (never prefix with `NEXT_PUBLIC_`)
5. **CORS**: Configure in Craft CMS to allow frontend origin
6. **ISR**: Use `next: { revalidate: N }` in fetch calls for incremental static regeneration
7. **Preview**: Use Craft's live preview with Next.js draft mode

